2":"1322","1453":"1453","1343":"1343","1310":"1310","1331":"1331","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","about 1343":"circa 1343","1319":"1319","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","Lurgashall, Sussex, England":"Lurgashall, Sussex, England","of Trotton, Sussex, England":"Trotton, Sussex, England"},"en":{"ca. 1318–":"about 1318–Deceased","1318–Female":"1318–Deceased","1319–Male":"1319–Deceased","1320–1363":"1320–1363","1322–Male":"1322–Deceased","1324–Male":"1324–Deceased","1326–Female":"1326–Deceased","1310–1364":"1310–1364","1334–Male":"1334–Deceased","1343–1394":"1343–1394","1283–1336":"1283–1336","1300–1331":"1300–1331","1363":"1363","1394":"1394","1382":"1382","1283":"1283","ca. 1318":"about 1318","1337":"1337","1326":"1326","before 20 May 1316":"before 20 May 1316","1336":"1336","1324":"1324","1334":"1334","1300":"1300","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1343":"1343","1310":"1310","1331":"1331","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","about 1343":"about 1343","1319":"1319","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","Lurgashall, Sussex, England":"Lurgashall, Sussex, England","of Trotton, Sussex, England":"Trotton, Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":10,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":19,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":64,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Camoys was born about 1318, in Trotton, Sussex, England, her father, Ralph de Camoys, was 36 and her mother, Elizabeth le Despenser, was 20. She married John Shelvestrode. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"ca. 1318–":"umbes 1318–Surnud","1318–Female":"1318–Surnud","1319–Male":"1319–Surnud","1320–1363":"1320–1363","1322–Male":"1322–Surnud","1324–Male":"1324–Surnud","1326–Female":"1326–Surnud","1310–1364":"1310–1364","1334–Male":"1334–Surnud","1343–1394":"1343–1394","1283–1336":"1283–1336","1300–1331":"1300–1331","1363":"1363","1394":"1394","1382":"1382","1283":"1283","ca. 1318":"umbes 1318","1337":"1337","1326":"1326","before 20 May 1316":"enne 20. maid 1316","1336":"1336","1324":"1324","1334":"1334","1300"